version_description: This is the iPhone Demo version of the song.
This version requires you to add a capo about halfway through, so swift hands are advised.
The original song is heavily electronic, but if you strip it of all its blips and bloops this is pretty much what it boils down to. I think.

This song is rhythmically pretty complex, there's some added notation to make things as clear as possible: 1) Chord names start directly above the word they change on, as usual. 2) An asterisk marks where there is a triplet. If this coincides with a chord change, the asterisk precedes the new chord. Otherwise, the triplet uses the previous chord. 3) In the interludes and outro, where there are no lyrics, there's a simplified measure notation. Each measure here is the length of two "strums" (the same length as the word "some" at the start of Verse 3). 4) In the outro, there are no strums (the recording simply has string sweeps), so here the asterisks simply mark the prolongation of the previous chord. The timing of the measures is still the same as in the interludes.
